        "id": "e1581bb32e13364c",
        "text": "_Scattered thoughts: \nWhen I was reading Jess' page [[Being in the Grey]] this term 'natural learners' appeared for me and I sensed that it was important to explore and define. Lauren recently introduced me to the concept of 'mirror neurons' through which babies learn – the neurons that allow one being to mirror the activity of another. I began to ponder this idea of mirroring as our core learning model. I then began to think about the difference between our experience of life when we mirror nature vs mirroring a machine. Learning that is organic and emerging - autopoietic, as opposed to defined traditional education that is structured as production line, mechanistic - allopoietic. We are alive, thrive, in [[Natural Order]]. Natural order vs. artificial order. Might we then talk about what it means to be a 'natural learner' vs an 'artificial learner'? Not sure... more to distill and explore... _"
