        "text": "_Scattered thoughts: \nWhen I was editing Jess' page [[Being in the Grey]] this term 'natural learners' came to me and I sensed that it was important to explore and define. A quick search discovers that others have used this term – [https://www.yournaturallearner.com/what-is-natural-learning/ here] and [https://naturalearning.org/ here]. I also recently was intrigued by a recent connection to Jenny Finn in the [https://thrivableworld.mn.co/share/iBDQHEry1A_jlVc8?utm_source=manual Thrivable World] group, learning about [https://springhouse.org/ Springhouse], her school - where they use the language of nature (vitality & regenerating culture) as they reimagine education. _\n\n_Lauren recently introduced me to the concept of [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirror_neuron mirror neurons] through which babies learn – the neurons that allow a baby to mirror the activity of an adult. I began to ponder this idea of mirroring as our core learning model. I then began to think about the difference between our experience of life when we mirror nature vs mirroring a machine. Learning that is organic and emerging - autopoietic, as unlike traditional education that is structured as production line, mechanistic - allopoietic. We thrive when we mirror [[Natural Order]] as opposed to that which imprisons our spirit when we mirror mechanistic artificial order. Might we then talk about what it means to be a 'natural learner' vs an 'artificial learner'? Not sure... more to explore and distill... _"
